\par
``the present-day organizational landscape in global financial standard setting continues to be characterized by fragmentation and a functional division of labor. Banking regulation is coordinated through the BCBS; the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is in charge of rules for securities markets and credit rating agencies. The International Accounting Standards Board (IASB) sets accounting standards for most of the world, with the notable exception of the United States, which has its own standard setter. Yet other facets of financial governance, for example the regulation of hedge funds, have been dealt with predominantly by national or European authorities, without a strong role for an international standard setter. The FSB provides some coordination between these organizations without, however, steering or directing their efforts in a meaningful way.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 195)
\par
``In contrast to the prevailing propensity for analytical separation, a small number of researchers have recently begun to reconnect the substantive and organizational'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 195)
\par
``debates'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 196)  +
\par
``This article builds on such work by analyzing how specific interdependencies at the substantive level create the need for tight coordination at the organizational level. Based on this analysis we develop our core argument that these two sides of financial governance should not be independently reformed or, for that matter, individually assessed'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 196)  \% Argument about interdependence of markets create the need for tight coordination across regulatory bodies
\par
``Reflexive finance implies that asset prices are endogenous to the system of rules governing financial markets, as well as to the broader social institutions in which that system is embedded. If this is indeed the case, then managing and controlling the interactions between different regulatory domains becomes a core function of global financial governance. This requires a sharp departure from the fragmented, decentralized cooperation model and the pursuit of significantly tighter coordination between regulatory domains than has hitherto been the case.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 196)
\par
``The fragmentation of banking regulation, accounting standards, and rules for credit rating agencies and derivatives trading represents a crucial obstacle in the way of effective and legitimate policy. As Minsky and others since him have emphasized, we should expect banks to use their room for maneuver to increase profitability by taking on additional risk. A faulty regulatory instrument for linking regulatory capital to balance sheet risks therefore constitutes a major weakness in the global regulatory edifice.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 197)
\par
``Obviously, we are not the first to criticize the fragmented arrangements of global finance.9 However, whereas previous criticisms highlighted how complex market players such as hedge funds ``fell between the cracks,'' our argument comes from a quite different angle. We explain how, given specific interdependencies between regulatory domains, the reflexivity of financial markets makes it imperative that these domains be governed as a whole. Yet global-level rule design is distributed over diverse organizations and neither the links between them, nor the umbrella provided by the Financial Stability Board, allow policymakers to integrate the substance of their standard-setting activities sufficiently.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 197)  \% Existing criticisms of the fragmented nature of the financial regulatory infrastructure.
\par
``Debating Global Financial Governance'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 198)  \#\#
\par
``International organizations concerned with financial regulation have grown incrementally since the 1970s, responding to crises as they have occurred.14 Following the 1997 Asian financial crisis, policymakers debated the need for what came to be called'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 198)
\par
``the International Financial Architecture, encompassing rules to cover all key domains of financial activity that needed addressing.15 To this end, the Financial Stability Forum was created in 1999 and charged with compiling existing standards in a Compendium of Standards and Codes.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 199)  +
\par
``critiques of the organizational architecture of global financial governance (but not the substance of their output) followed a different line, arguing that the range of countries with real influence was unfairly restricted to a small subset of Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) member states and effectively excluded the Global South'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 199)  \% Criticism of the architecture of glboal financial governance on the ground of limited accountability
