``the chief criticism remained, as in precrisis times, the skewed representation in favor of the OECD world.24 The appointment of the G20 to global financial leadership and the broader representation in the BCBS seemed to address that grievance,25 even if worries persisted that global financial governance remained exposed to excessive business influence.26 In contrast, there was no prominent call for an overhaul of the organizational architecture. Indeed, a range of critics called for a continued decentralization of governance, mostly in order to allow financial rules to be better tailored to locally diverse economic and political contexts.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 199)  \% Summary of the debate on the reforms after the global financial crisis
