``Equilibrium and Reflexive Finance'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 199)  \#\#
\par
``Substance and Institutions in Setting Capital Requirements'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 202)  \#\#
\par
``the actual impact of any particular percentage capital requirement (C) depends on how banking capital (A) and risk-weighted assets (B) are defined and measured. And while the BCBS sets the numerical level of (C), the definitions of the elements underlying (A) and (B), and the standards for measuring them, are set by several different actors working in different regulatory domains'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 203)
\par
``Coordination between standard-setting bodies was a key concern at the G20's London summit in early 2009. Here the G20 decided to upgrade the Financial Stability Forum to the Financial Stability Board (FSB), with a permanent secretariat at the Bank for International Settlements in Basel. Following this upgrade, the FSB was formally mandated to coordinate at the international level the work of national financial authorities and international standard setting bodies (SSBs) in order to develop and promote the implementation of effective regulatory, supervisory and other financial sector policies.48'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 204)  \% Strengthening of the FSB after the GFC
\par
``However, as Helleiner has pointed out, the FSB is in a weak position vis-\`a-vis standard setters; Lombardi echoes this conclusion.49 The underlying problem is that the FSB lacks ``hard'' instruments to elicit such coordination. However, it can use suasion behind the scenes, and wield influence via the progress reports it publishes on standard setting.50 The FSB can also count on the governments that sponsor its work to support coordination efforts between organizations that have those same governments as members. For these reasons, achieving cooperation between the BCBS and IOSCO is relatively unproblematic, and indeed has a long history. In contrast, the FSB is much less influential when one or more of the relevant bodies is not an intergovernmental organization (the IASB is not), or when key standards are not set multilaterally at all (those for credit rating agencies and derivatives trading are not).'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 204)  \% Role of the FSB vis-a-vis standard-setters
\par
``In light of these deficiencies, it is unsurprising that we find no evidence that the FSB has succeeded in fostering greater coherence across the different regulatory domains addressed in this article (see column 3 of Table 1, above).51 On the contrary, at the outset the FSB's influence was strongly resisted by, among others, the IASB, explicitly concerning the notion that accounting standard setting might be drawn into a macroprudential agenda.52 In response, the FSB has since avoided involvement in substantive accounting debates, even though these are crucial to banking regulation and many of the other regulatory domains with which the FSB deals.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 204)  \% Limited impact of the FSB in promoting coordination among standard-setters
\par
``The Numerator: Accounting Standard Setters and the Basel Committee'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 204)  \#\#
\par
``On the one hand, banking regulators specify which elements on a bank's accounting statements can count as capital (BCBS standards).'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 204)
\par
