``Unable to find a satisfactory compromise with accounting standard setters, the BCBS has, over the past two decades, sought to define the elements of bank capital more directly itself. The underlying data still come from accounting, but the BCBS has departed from the accountants' standard aggregates and instead constructed its own alternatives.56 Most notably, in order to ensure the common equity part of bank capital is of the ``highest quality,'' the BCBS has developed a special banking version of this aggregate. Whereas the IASB's and FASB's definitions of common equity are relatively broad,57 the BCBS version is narrowed by an extensive list of exclusions and adjustments.58'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 205)
\par
``Nevertheless, despite such efforts, there is still a strict limit as to how far the BCBS can insulate its capital standards from decisions taken by the accounting standard setters. This is because, as the crisis demonstrated, the most significant part of a bank's capital for absorbing losses comes from retained profits, which cannot be compiled without recourse to accounting aggregates.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 205)
\par
``A second example of accounting standards disrupting the calibration of capital requirements is via measurement methods. The IASB and FASB continue to develop standards for financial assets that offer banks the scope to choose between two fundamentally different ways of measuring assets: historic cost and fair value.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 206)
\par
``regardless of which accounting measurement method (or combination of them) is chosen, that choice ought to be made in close coordination with the BCBS because it has such a significant impact on the working of capital standards.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 206)
