``the specifications of the denominator are defined partly by the BCBS, and partly by either the CRAs or the banks' internal ratings departments. In the case of derivatives and certain other complex financial instruments\textemdash key ingredients of large banks' balance sheets\textemdash an additional role in risk assessment is played by the Committee on Payment and Settlement Systems in its joint work with the International Organization of Securities Commissions (known together as CPSS-IOSCO and examined further below).'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 208)
\par
``Risk weighting and its governance'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 209)  \#\#\#
\par
``CRAs have traditionally fallen under the responsibility of IOSCO, which in 2004 endorsed a voluntary code of conduct for CRAs following the failure of credit ratings exposed by a series of corporate scandals on both sides of the Atlantic in the early 2000s.87 The voluntary nature of the code meant, however, that effective governance was left in the hands of national or, in the case of the EU, regional authorities.'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 209)
\par
``In a third set of initiatives explicitly addressing the regulation of risk rating, the Basel Committee, European Commission, and US Congress have, since 2010, been'' (M\"ugge and Perry, 2014, p. 209)
